notes:
J.B. Holmes entered the final round of the 2014 Wells Fargo Championship with a one-stroke lead over Martin Flores. Despite an early bogey on the par-3 second hole and late bogeys on Nos. 16 and 18, Holmes'1-under 71 was just enough to hold off a final-round charge by Jim Furyk, who closed with the round of the day(7-under 65)to finish one stroke back. The win, the third of Holmes'PGA TOUR career, came in his 187th PGA TOUR start at the age of 32 years, eight days. In seven previous starts at the Wells Fargo Championship, Holmes'had just one top-10 finish, a tie for ninth 2011.   
   
 With his win at the 2014 Wells Fargo Championship, J.B. Holmes becomes just the fourth third-round leader/co-leader to carry that lead to victory at the Wells Fargo Championship, joining David Toms (2003), Jim Furyk (2006)and Anthony Kim (2008). The other 54-hole leaders averaged 73.77 in the final round, with none breaking par.  
  
 The runner-up finish for Jim Furyk at the 2014 Wells Fargo Championship was the 26th of his career and first since the 2013 PGA Championship. The finish was also his fifth top-10 finish in 10 starts at the Wells Fargo Championship(won in 2006, second in 2014, tied for second in 2005, was seventh in-2008 and tied for seventh in 2010).  
  
   Derek Ernst tied for 30th in his bid to become the first player to successfully defend his title at the Wells Fargo Championship.  
  
   Phil Mickelson made his 11th cut in 11 starts at the Wells Fargo Championship, tying for 11th. He owns seven top-10s at Quail Hollow Club:   
   
   Year  Finish   
2004, Tied for fifth  
  
2005, Tied for seventh  
2007, Tied for third  
2009, Tied for fifth  
2010, Second  
2011, Tied for ninth  
2013, Third  
  
On his 25th birthday in 2014, Rory McIlroy earned his fourth top-10 finish in five starts at the Wells Fargo Championship, tying for eighth. He won in 2010, missed the cut in 2011, tied for second in 2012 and tied for 10th in 2013.  
  
 After opening the 2014 Wells Fargo Championship with an 8-over 80(was tied for last place), Brendon de Jonge responded with rounds of 62-68-69 to tie for sixth. His second-round 10-under 62 tied the tournament-course record.  
  
   Lucas Glover, the 2011 Wells Fargo Championship winner, remains the only player in the tournament history to post all four rounds in the 60s.   
   
 Four players competed in all 12 tournaments at Quail Hollow Club since the tournament's inception in 2003: J.J. Henry ;   Stuart Appleby ;   Charles Howell III ; and Rory Sabbatini.
